title: La NASA y CSA asignarán astronautas para Artemis II
summary: La NASA y la Agencia Espacial Canadiense (CSA, por sus siglas en inglés) anunciarán los cuatro astronautas que se aventurarán a los alrededores de la Luna. El anuncio se dará durante un acto que se celebrará a las 11 a.m. EDT (10 a.m. CDT) del lunes 3 de abril en el Campo Ellington del Centro Espacial Johnson de la NASA en Houston.

title: NASA, Canadian Space Agency to Assign Artemis II Moon Astronauts
summary: NASA and CSA (Canadian Space Agency) will announce during an event at 11 a.m. EDT (10 a.m. CDT) on Monday, April 3, from NASA Johnson Space Center’s Ellington Field in Houston, the four astronauts who will venture around the Moon. title: Momentus preparing for Vigoride thruster test as it ships next vehicle
summary: In-space transportation company Momentus is gearing up for a key test of one orbital transfer vehicle as it ships another for launch next month.

title: China is developing a quantum communications satellite network
summary: Chinese research institutes are working to construct a quantum communications network using satellites in low and medium-to-high Earth orbits.

title: Hughes unveils Jupiter 3
summary: Hughes Network System unveiled Jupiter 3, a massive geostationary communications satellite built by Maxar Technologies.

title: Atlas joins forces with Viasat RTE
summary: Through a partnership with Viasat Real-Time Earth, Atlas Space Operations will expand its antenna network and offer customers access to larger antennas.

title: SpaceX completes final dedicated launch for OneWeb
summary: SpaceX deployed 40 more satellites for OneWeb March 9 in its third and final dedicated mission for the British broadband operator, which is now just one launch away from having enough spacecraft to provide global services.

title: NASA Tracking Newly Discovered Earth Bound Asteroid
summary: NASA's Planetary Defense Coordination Office recently announced the discovery of a new asteroid that has the potential to collide with Earth.

title: SpaceX launches and lands rocket on mission for OneWeb
summary: SpaceX launched a Falcon 9 rocket from Cape Canaveral Space Force Station Thursday with 40 more internet satellites for rival OneWeb, followed eight minutes later by the landing of the rocket’s first stage booster back at the Florida spaceport. Liftoff of the Falcon 9 rocket occurred at 2:13 p.m. EST (1913 GMT).
